data.title: In A Cowslip's Bell I Lie
data.meta_description: Side blog: @hello-robin-goodfellow  Right-wingers (or the centrists who trust then in the name of "freedom of speech"), sexists, racists, ableists and queer fobics: do not interact.
data.text:
“Sleep, those little slices of death — how I loathe them…”

Edgar Allan Poe.

Perhaps he is correct. The waking from a dream that is not yet to be, yet haunts my psyche as if the devil himself has picked me from the fray of his rope. Though to call it a dream would be a simple blunder of nomenclature. No, no dreams elicits peace, calm, a sweetness we ever yearn for in our brief encounters of what it is like to be with the dead.

A silence no mortal man truly knows till he’s breathes his last breath. Though the closest of which could come for my the mistake I’ve called my visions in the night, whispers of not memories but what to come. To know death is to face her, to shake her hand and follow her, to let that very last moment of your long journey of life end. “To die to sleep. To sleep perchance to dream.”

But this is not a dream that haunts me. No. Dreams are not haunting ghouls of the mind, no no no. That is not it. Visions of agony, torment, despair, fill my minds eye when I have slept. No, these are not dreams, these are nightmares.

Though I dare to say if I should even call them that. They’re long and distant yet they worry me. I have never been a man of visions. There is no rational explanation for that, when a telepath has not accessed my mind. I would feel it, understand it. Perhaps fear ebbs away at my fragile consciousness when I slumber. Perhaps indeed.

“To die, to sleep, no more. And by a sleep we say to end.”
